'Cangjie programming language_collection_HashMap_collection_hashmap_properties': 'In Cangjie code language, HashMap ensures that each key is unique.
HashMap instances with different key-value types are considered different types and cannot be assigned to each other.'

Error_case_code:
var map1 = HashMap<String, Int64>()
var map2 = HashMap<Int64, String>()
map2 = map1 // This will cause a compile-time error

'Cangjie programming language_collection_HashMap_collection_hashmap_traversal': 'In Cangjie code language, You can use a for-in loop to iterate through all key-value pairs in a HashMap. Note that HashMap does not guarantee the order of elements, so the traversal order may differ from the insertion order.'

Code_Example:
import std.collection.*


main() {
    let map = HashMap<String, Int64>([("a", 0), ("b", 1), ("c", 2)])
    for ((k, v) in map) {
        println("The key is ${k}, the value is ${v}")
    }
}

'Cangjie programming language_collection_HashMap_collection_hashmap_size': 'In Cangjie code language, You can use the size property to get the number of key-value pairs in a HashMap.'

Code_Example:
import std.collection.*


main() {
    let map = HashMap<String, Int64>([("a", 0), ("b", 1), ("c", 2)])
    if (map.size == 0) {
        println("This is an empty hashmap")
    } else {
        println("The size of hashmap is ${map.size}")
    }
}

'Cangjie programming language_collection_HashMap_collection_hashmap_modifying': 'In Cangjie code language, HashMap is a mutable reference type that provides the ability to modify elements, add elements, and delete elements.HashMap variability is a very useful feature that allows all references to the same HashMap instance to share the same element and modify them uniformly.
 You can use the subscript syntax to modify the value of a key.
If you need to add a single key-value pair to the HashMap, use the put function. If you want to add multiple key-value pairs at the same time, you can use the putAll function. When the key does not exist, the put function performs the added operation, and when the key exists, the put function overwrites the old value with the new value.
In addition to using the put function, you can also use assignment to add new key-value pairs directly to the HashMap.
To delete an element from the HashMap, you can use the remove function, which requires you to specify the key to be deleted.'

Code_Example:
//the subscript syntax to modify
let map1 = HashMap<String, Int64>([("a", 0), ("b", 1), ("c", 2)])
map1["a"] = 3
//put or putAll
let map2 = HashMap<String, Int64>()
map2.put("a", 0) // map2 contains the element ("a", 0)
map2.put("b", 1) // map2 contains the elements ("a", 0), ("b", 1)
let map3 = HashMap<String, Int64>([("c", 2), ("d", 3)])
map2.putAll(map3) // map2 contains the elements ("a", 0), ("b", 1), ("c", 2), ("d", 3)
//remove
let map4 = HashMap<String, Int64>([("a", 0), ("b", 1), ("c", 2), ("d", 3)])
map4.remove("d") // map contains the elements ("a", 0), ("b", 1), ("c", 2)

'Cangjie programming language_collection_HashMap_collection_hashmap_references': 'In Cangjie code language, HashMap is a reference type, meaning that all references to the same HashMap instance share the same data. Modifications to the elements of a HashMap affect all references to that instance.'

Code_Example:
let map1 = HashMap<String, Int64>([("a", 0), ("b", 1), ("c", 2)])
let map2 = map1
map2["a"] = 3
// map1 contains the elements ("a", 3), ("b", 1), ("c", 2)
// map2 contains the elements ("a", 3), ("b", 1), ("c", 2)
